01:36:16.080 --> 01:36:17.130
Hi, I'm Hans Schattle.

01:36:17.130 --> 01:36:19.290
I teach in the political
science department

01:36:19.290 --> 01:36:21.660
at Yonsei University
in Seoul, South Korea.

01:36:21.660 --> 01:36:24.150
But New England's my
home, so it's really nice

01:36:24.150 --> 01:36:25.930
to see you here in person.

01:36:25.930 --> 01:36:27.780
I followed your
career trajectory back

01:36:27.780 --> 01:36:29.170
in the early 1990s.

01:36:29.170 --> 01:36:31.920
I was working as a news
reporter locally at the time

01:36:31.920 --> 01:36:33.197
here in Massachusetts.

01:36:33.197 --> 01:36:35.280
And it was really something
to see your dispatches

01:36:35.280 --> 01:36:39.600
in the Boston Globe during the
Bosnian War, and of course,

01:36:39.600 --> 01:36:41.130
everything that's followed.

01:36:41.130 --> 01:36:44.550
One of my big frustrations
in international relations

01:36:44.550 --> 01:36:47.100
is that we talk so much
about balance of power,

01:36:47.100 --> 01:36:51.300
and understandably so, but
we give correspondingly

01:36:51.300 --> 01:36:55.410
little airtime to the idea
of balancing responsibility.

01:36:55.410 --> 01:36:58.917
So I'm wondering, in your years
in government, and especially

01:36:58.917 --> 01:37:00.750
at the United Nations
in the last few years,

01:37:00.750 --> 01:37:05.070
did you come away from that
time with any new insights that

01:37:05.070 --> 01:37:08.490
could inspire us a little bit
about how we might think more

01:37:08.490 --> 01:37:11.310
comprehensively,
maybe holistically,

01:37:11.310 --> 01:37:13.680
about how to manage
responsibilities

01:37:13.680 --> 01:37:17.100
on issues, global warming,
migrants, refugees?

01:37:17.100 --> 01:37:19.830
We could, of course, talk
about R2P and the difficulty

01:37:19.830 --> 01:37:22.590
in rehabilitating that
concept after Libya.

01:37:22.590 --> 01:37:25.920
I mean, IR now is so much
bigger than just diplomacy,

01:37:25.920 --> 01:37:27.030
foreign ministries.

01:37:27.030 --> 01:37:28.740
We have corporations.

01:37:28.740 --> 01:37:32.190
Look at Davos this week, NGOs,
schools and universities,

01:37:32.190 --> 01:37:34.870
churches, everyday
citizens on Twitter.

01:37:34.870 --> 01:37:35.370
And

01:37:35.370 --> 01:37:36.870
There's so much out
there and I feel

01:37:36.870 --> 01:37:39.300
as if there's a lot of work
in the field that's still

01:37:39.300 --> 01:37:41.400
ahead of us in terms
of consolidating

01:37:41.400 --> 01:37:44.310
our thinking about how
we can solve problems

01:37:44.310 --> 01:37:46.980
more effectively that
transcend nation states.

01:37:46.980 --> 01:37:48.720
And of course, the UN is our--

01:37:48.720 --> 01:37:51.510
it's the best venue we've
got, but it only goes so far.

01:37:51.510 --> 01:37:53.560
So any thoughts on that
would be really great.

01:37:53.560 --> 01:37:54.060
Great.

01:37:54.060 --> 01:37:56.310
Thank you.

01:37:56.310 --> 01:37:58.871
Great, OK.

