And thanks for staying
through all of this.

01:38:03.500 --> 01:38:05.376
It's OK if you
have to leave, too.

01:38:09.610 --> 01:38:12.580
So first, for the aspiring
political organizer--

01:38:12.580 --> 01:38:15.760
Liam, I think you
said your name was--

01:38:15.760 --> 01:38:17.770
we learned yesterday
at Radcliffe,

01:38:17.770 --> 01:38:23.410
through-- or two days ago
at Radcliffe that only 24%

01:38:23.410 --> 01:38:27.070
of eligible Harvard students
had voted in the midterm

01:38:27.070 --> 01:38:32.110
election in 2014.

01:38:32.110 --> 01:38:35.680
Aspiring political organizer,
there's a task for you.

01:38:35.680 --> 01:38:37.900
Why don't we all chip
in and figure out

01:38:37.900 --> 01:38:42.520
how we can get that up just
way, way higher, as something

01:38:42.520 --> 01:38:45.499
we can do in the here and now?

01:38:45.499 --> 01:38:48.040
But your question was about how
to talk about foreign policy.

01:38:48.040 --> 01:38:54.970
And I guess I would
acknowledge that we have-- we,

01:38:54.970 --> 01:38:57.430
the Obama administration,
did not crack that code,

01:38:57.430 --> 01:38:59.230
it's fair to say.

01:38:59.230 --> 01:39:02.200
The fact that we now
have not only the Trump

01:39:02.200 --> 01:39:05.380
base with "America
First" and this kind

01:39:05.380 --> 01:39:10.000
of discredited
political ideology

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:13.510
that has lived within our
political ecosystem for more

01:39:13.510 --> 01:39:18.200
than a hundred years, but the
fact that that is now governing

01:39:18.200 --> 01:39:21.760
and that we're pulling out
of the kinds of things that

01:39:21.760 --> 01:39:24.220
put my world view to
one side, but just

01:39:24.220 --> 01:39:28.480
as a matter of
pragmatism, are needed,

01:39:28.480 --> 01:39:31.720
whether on climate or
on terrorism, alienating

01:39:31.720 --> 01:39:34.450
our allies or
insulting our allies,

01:39:34.450 --> 01:39:37.810
and thus really
jeopardizing our ability

01:39:37.810 --> 01:39:39.380
to call on them
when we need them,

01:39:39.380 --> 01:39:41.755
whether in the context of
international framework or even

01:39:41.755 --> 01:39:42.680
just bilaterally.

01:39:42.680 --> 01:39:47.020
So the fact that it's on
the left and the right--

01:39:47.020 --> 01:39:49.405
and I'm not a believer
in false equivalence,

01:39:49.405 --> 01:39:51.280
because only one party
is governing and doing

01:39:51.280 --> 01:39:52.610
these things.

01:39:52.610 --> 01:39:59.140
But the left wing of
the Democratic Party

01:39:59.140 --> 01:40:00.940
is not very enthusiastic about--

01:40:00.940 --> 01:40:02.800
or some of them,
anyway, are not very

01:40:02.800 --> 01:40:06.250
enthusiastic about the
kinds of investments

01:40:06.250 --> 01:40:09.340
in our national security,
whether in the form

01:40:09.340 --> 01:40:12.100
of our military or our
diplomacy or in terms

01:40:12.100 --> 01:40:13.490
of international engagements.

01:40:13.490 --> 01:40:16.970
And so this-- these
wings are very different.

01:40:16.970 --> 01:40:20.410
And one has a much
more inclusive model

01:40:20.410 --> 01:40:22.600
and doesn't have the
xenophobia and racism

01:40:22.600 --> 01:40:23.720
or any of that stuff.

01:40:23.720 --> 01:40:27.310
But in terms of the
belief of the balance

01:40:27.310 --> 01:40:30.040
between the domestic
enterprise and all

01:40:30.040 --> 01:40:36.280
that is left to be done here
at home and what we do abroad,

01:40:36.280 --> 01:40:40.060
there ends up being an overlap,
at times, in prescription.

01:40:40.060 --> 01:40:41.800
So that worries me a lot.

01:40:41.800 --> 01:40:45.670
And on communications,
I've talked

01:40:45.670 --> 01:40:51.220
to some of my favorite members
of Congress about this.

01:40:51.220 --> 01:40:53.920
We have to find a way
to talk about climate

01:40:53.920 --> 01:40:56.920
that feels relevant to
people's lives here.

01:40:56.920 --> 01:40:59.410
And it won't be by talking
about the Paris Agreement.

01:40:59.410 --> 01:41:03.790
And some people ask me
sometimes about my book

01:41:03.790 --> 01:41:05.860
and is there a thesis
undergirding it.

01:41:05.860 --> 01:41:08.020
And the only thing I can
tell you is I will not--

01:41:08.020 --> 01:41:09.700
the words "liberal
international order"

01:41:09.700 --> 01:41:11.440
will not appear in my book.

01:41:11.440 --> 01:41:16.430
I aspire in telling
stories to reach people.

01:41:16.430 --> 01:41:20.530
Yes, that is my
unconcealed worldview,

01:41:20.530 --> 01:41:22.690
is that we have to invest
in our common security

01:41:22.690 --> 01:41:24.310
and our common humanity.

01:41:24.310 --> 01:41:26.129
But I've got to
find a way and we've

01:41:26.129 --> 01:41:27.670
got to find a way
to communicate that

01:41:27.670 --> 01:41:33.580
in a manner that's accessible
beyond our like-minded cohort.

01:41:33.580 --> 01:41:35.660
So I don't have a great answer.

01:41:35.660 --> 01:41:40.670
But I think this question
of how to communicate,

01:41:40.670 --> 01:41:43.090
how to talk about foreign
policy is really important.

01:41:43.090 --> 01:41:45.100
And we went through
this on Ebola.

01:41:45.100 --> 01:41:47.050
One thing President
Obama did, which

01:41:47.050 --> 01:41:49.000
I really admired
at the time, but I

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:52.390
think has to be
supplemented, is people

01:41:52.390 --> 01:41:54.790
were in full-on panic in
this country about Ebola.

01:41:54.790 --> 01:41:57.100
You remember when patient
Duncan died in Texas

01:41:57.100 --> 01:41:59.260
and some of the
nurses got infected.

01:41:59.260 --> 01:42:02.500
And the polling was horrific,
even in democratic districts,

01:42:02.500 --> 01:42:04.992
of people wanting
to close our doors

01:42:04.992 --> 01:42:07.450
and not even let health workers
come back into this country

01:42:07.450 --> 01:42:09.619
or to quarantine them
when they came back in.

01:42:09.619 --> 01:42:11.410
And this was at a time
where more Americans

01:42:11.410 --> 01:42:16.300
had married Kardashians than
had died of Ebola, right?

01:42:16.300 --> 01:42:17.920
And so President
Obama didn't say

01:42:17.920 --> 01:42:19.990
what I just said, which would--

01:42:19.990 --> 01:42:22.330
of course, you're not going to--

01:42:22.330 --> 01:42:25.210
I went to West Africa in the
middle of the Ebola crisis.

01:42:25.210 --> 01:42:25.900
I was scared.

01:42:25.900 --> 01:42:27.490
I mean, fear is--

01:42:27.490 --> 01:42:31.870
it's a legitimate thing
that one can feel.

01:42:31.870 --> 01:42:37.090
But how to meet people
where they are and--

01:42:37.090 --> 01:42:42.100
if you just, whether on
terrorism, refugees, Ebola,

01:42:42.100 --> 01:42:46.150
climate-- if you just cite
statistics for people,

01:42:46.150 --> 01:42:48.020
a lot of people,
that's good enough.

01:42:48.020 --> 01:42:51.850
But there's a group that
aren't-- the Trump base,

01:42:51.850 --> 01:42:53.690
but of people who
can be convinced,

01:42:53.690 --> 01:42:56.500
but whom we have not
brought into the fold,

01:42:56.500 --> 01:42:59.650
for whom statistics and just
the facts aren't meeting them

01:42:59.650 --> 01:43:02.170
viscerally where they are when
they are feeling those fears,

01:43:02.170 --> 01:43:03.880
which of course
are stoked, then,

01:43:03.880 --> 01:43:06.520
by people who shouldn't
be-- who should know better.

01:43:06.520 --> 01:43:10.190
In terms of tech companies, let
me-- let me just acknowledge,

01:43:10.190 --> 01:43:15.620
I think, the importance of the
question in the following way.

01:43:15.620 --> 01:43:18.000
People ask us about the
Russia interference,

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:19.970
which I'm surprised
I haven't been asked

01:43:19.970 --> 01:43:22.375
about, and with good reason.

01:43:22.375 --> 01:43:24.000
And they ask, should
we have done more?

01:43:24.000 --> 01:43:27.170
And should Obama have come out
and not just the intelligence

01:43:27.170 --> 01:43:28.640
agencies before the election?

01:43:28.640 --> 01:43:30.052
And all the rest and--

01:43:30.052 --> 01:43:32.510
we're all going to be asking
ourselves questions about what

01:43:32.510 --> 01:43:33.801
we might have done differently.

01:43:33.801 --> 01:43:39.900
But one thing I just want
to convey is when we--

01:43:39.900 --> 01:43:44.510
so cyber security and cyber
threats by foreign nations

01:43:44.510 --> 01:43:47.270
is something that we have
developed over the last decade,

01:43:47.270 --> 01:43:50.240
plus an infrastructure within
the US national security

01:43:50.240 --> 01:43:52.610
establishment to deal with,
Department of Justice,

01:43:52.610 --> 01:43:54.860
Department of Homeland
Security, Defense Department,

01:43:54.860 --> 01:43:57.530
intelligence in terms
of who's doing what.

01:43:57.530 --> 01:43:59.930
When it comes to
fake news and ad

01:43:59.930 --> 01:44:03.350
buys and your-- the
de-centralized world

01:44:03.350 --> 01:44:07.820
of your existence and
other citizens' existence,

01:44:07.820 --> 01:44:10.370
whether here or
anywhere else, there's

01:44:10.370 --> 01:44:12.920
no obvious government lever.

01:44:12.920 --> 01:44:15.920
And that's why this
conversation that's

01:44:15.920 --> 01:44:19.430
happening in Silicon Valley, as
unsatisfying as I have found it

01:44:19.430 --> 01:44:22.010
up to this point, really
is a conversation that

01:44:22.010 --> 01:44:24.614
should have been happening
four or five years ago.

01:44:24.614 --> 01:44:26.030
And we should have
done everything

01:44:26.030 --> 01:44:27.946
in our power-- we should
have done more to try

01:44:27.946 --> 01:44:30.890
to catalyze that conversation.

01:44:30.890 --> 01:44:34.250
But fundamentally, it's going to
be on that community of people

01:44:34.250 --> 01:44:36.170
to make things happen.

01:44:36.170 --> 01:44:39.620
And then I just merged
the last two questions

01:44:39.620 --> 01:44:46.580
because [? Gees' ?] question was
on how to stop crises and share

01:44:46.580 --> 01:44:48.860
burdens better, and then
the other was on balance

01:44:48.860 --> 01:44:51.020
of responsibility,
which I think also

01:44:51.020 --> 01:44:52.807
is another version
of burden-sharing.

01:44:52.807 --> 01:44:54.890
Part of the answer to the
first question about how

01:44:54.890 --> 01:44:57.890
you sell foreign
policy in a broader way

01:44:57.890 --> 01:45:00.830
will entail being able
to better describe

01:45:00.830 --> 01:45:03.500
what the international
order is buying us.

01:45:03.500 --> 01:45:06.110
And Donald Trump has had this
worldview throughout his life.

01:45:06.110 --> 01:45:08.420
He has not changed at all.

01:45:08.420 --> 01:45:11.090
He feels like we are
getting ripped off.

01:45:11.090 --> 01:45:13.290
And he has found something,
again, in his base,

01:45:13.290 --> 01:45:15.410
but also in others
who have supported him

01:45:15.410 --> 01:45:17.750
and now may have--
maybe have melted away.

01:45:17.750 --> 01:45:20.330
But we need to
show-- for instance,

01:45:20.330 --> 01:45:23.780
in my world of UN peacekeeping,
everybody focuses on the fact

01:45:23.780 --> 01:45:28.460
that it's a $8.5 billion budget
for UN peacekeepers, 100,000 UN

01:45:28.460 --> 01:45:31.790
peacekeepers in the world,
and we pay 28% of that.

01:45:31.790 --> 01:45:33.860
They don't focus on
the fact that 72%

01:45:33.860 --> 01:45:35.720
is paid for by other countries.

01:45:35.720 --> 01:45:38.180
And moreover, the troops who
actually are peacekeepers,

01:45:38.180 --> 01:45:41.360
who are risking their lives and
dying at record rates almost

01:45:41.360 --> 01:45:42.830
never come from
the United States.

01:45:42.830 --> 01:45:45.290
We have a tiny
percentage of that.

01:45:45.290 --> 01:45:48.170
Climate, I think we
made good headway.

01:45:48.170 --> 01:45:50.870
But responsibility is something
you hear a lot from the biggest

01:45:50.870 --> 01:45:53.810
emitters, from China and India.

01:45:53.810 --> 01:45:56.450
And their conception
of responsibility

01:45:56.450 --> 01:45:58.689
is historical, which
is really important.

01:45:58.689 --> 01:46:00.480
If you're them, you're
like, wait a minute.

01:46:00.480 --> 01:46:02.230
How can we just start
caring about climate

01:46:02.230 --> 01:46:04.970
when we are now needing coal
in order to develop and deal

01:46:04.970 --> 01:46:06.470
with our growing populations?

01:46:06.470 --> 01:46:08.360
And I think what we
succeeded in doing,

01:46:08.360 --> 01:46:10.910
partly by leveraging the
relationships that Obama had

01:46:10.910 --> 01:46:15.530
built with Xi and with Modi,
is for the first time now

01:46:15.530 --> 01:46:20.180
we have a language about
responsibility that is lateral

01:46:20.180 --> 01:46:24.290
and in the present about
emissions as being what

01:46:24.290 --> 01:46:26.220
dictates your responsibility.

01:46:26.220 --> 01:46:28.190
But we still have to
acknowledge the historical

01:46:28.190 --> 01:46:30.120
and the disparities
and so forth there.

01:46:30.120 --> 01:46:33.890
So I think a lot of creative
thinking needs to be done.

01:46:33.890 --> 01:46:37.760
And the questions that
emphasize language and framing

01:46:37.760 --> 01:46:41.120
are right because we
have to do better.

01:46:41.120 --> 01:46:44.600
If we are going to go
forward and actually

01:46:44.600 --> 01:46:48.410
be able to execute a worldview
that is rooted in the sense

01:46:48.410 --> 01:46:50.690
that we are connected and
that it is in our interests,

01:46:50.690 --> 01:46:53.905
also, to look out for others,
whether at home or abroad,

01:46:53.905 --> 01:46:55.280
we're going to
have to sell that.

01:46:55.280 --> 01:46:55.880
Thank you.

01:46:55.880 --> 01:46:57.980
[APPLAUSE]

